│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp"], [5200, 5220,              │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1.          │
│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe verifier reports \"Instruction does not         │
│ dominate all uses\" for IR created by SLP vectorizer: an insertelement of a   │
│ pointer value and a subsequent shufflevector. This means the pass inserted a  │
│ newly built vector (or a splat/shuffle derived from it) at an insertion point │
│ in a basic block that does not dominate all the places where the vector is    │
│ used. With the provided reproducer, the CFG has many disjoint blocks and      │
│ phis; SLP likely builds a vector from a scalar pointer (%arg) and uses it     │
│ across blocks. If the builder's insertion point is set too late (inside a     │
│ specific block), users in other blocks can be reached that are not dominated  │
│ by that location, causing the verifier to abort.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's        │
│ Log:\n- ScalarEvolution analysis shows most loads/phis are poison; this       │
│ demonstrates minimal constraints and increases SLP's tendency to create       │
│ vector constructs early.\n- The first visible failure occurs during           │
│ verification after slp-vectorizer runs. The printed broken IR snippet         │
│ shows:\n  %1 = insertelement <2 x ptr addrspace(1)> poison, ptr addrspace(1)  │
│ %arg, i32 0\n  %0 = shufflevector <2 x ptr addrspace(1)> %1, <2 x ptr         │
│ addrspace(1)> poison, <2 x i32> zeroinitializer\nThese are classic patterns   │
│ when broadcasting/splatting a scalar into a vector (insert then shuffle). The │
│ problem is dominance - not the operation semantics themselves.\n- Grep did    │
│ not find explicit references to InsertElement or ShuffleVector in             │
│ SLPVectorizer.cpp due to templates/indirection, but given SLP’s behavior, it  │
│ constructs vectors for gathers/scatters via helper methods. The issue is      │
│ consistent with incorrect choice of insertion point when creating these       │
│ vector instructions.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nSLPVectorizer places newly   │
│ created vector instructions at an insertion point based on one of the scalar  │
│ instructions in the tree (often the \"getInsertionPoint\" of the scheduling   │
│ region or a representative instruction). In CFGs with many branches and phis, │
│ some users of the newly built vector may reside in different blocks that are  │
│ not dominated by the chosen insertion point. Creating a broadcast vector of a │
│ pointer (%arg) in a specific block and then using it in non-dominated blocks  │
│ triggers the verifier error.\nTherefore, the root cause is that SLP's         │
│ building code for pointer-gather/broadcast constructs uses an insertion point │
│ that does not dominate all uses. The fix is to ensure that when creating such │
│ vectors that might be shared across blocks, the insertion point is moved to a │
│ location that dominates all intended users. Typically, this is either the     │
│ function entry block's first insertion point or the nearest common dominator  │
│ of all users.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n- Edit Point 1 (lines 236-244 in │
│ SLPVectorizer.cpp): Extend isValidElementType/getValueType logic to           │
│ explicitly treat vector-of-pointers as legal but ensure the builder uses a    │
│ dominance-safe insertion point when forming broadcast/splat sequences from    │
│ pointer values.\n  Suggested change: Add a utility to compute a safe          │
│ insertion point (e.g., nearest common dominator of all planned uses) and      │
