│ \"Instruction does not dominate all uses\" for IR created by SLP vectorizer:  │
│ an insertelement of a pointer value and a subsequent shufflevector. This      │
│ means the pass inserted a newly built vector (or a splat/shuffle derived from │
│ it) at an insertion point in a basic block that does not dominate all the     │
│ places where the vector is used. With the provided reproducer, the CFG has    │
│ many disjoint blocks and phis; SLP likely builds a vector from a scalar       │
│ pointer (%arg) and uses it across blocks. If the builder's insertion point is │
│ set too late (inside a specific block), users in other blocks can be reached  │
│ that are not dominated by that location, causing the verifier to abort.\n\n2. │
│ Analyzing opt's Log:\n- ScalarEvolution analysis shows most loads/phis are    │
│ poison; this demonstrates minimal constraints and increases SLP's tendency to │
│ create vector constructs early.\n- The first visible failure occurs during    │
│ verification after slp-vectorizer runs. The printed broken IR snippet         │
│ shows:\n  %1 = insertelement <2 x ptr addrspace(1)> poison, ptr addrspace(1)  │
│ %arg, i32 0\n  %0 = shufflevector <2 x ptr addrspace(1)> %1, <2 x ptr         │
│ addrspace(1)> poison, <2 x i32> zeroinitializer\nThese are classic patterns   │
│ when broadcasting/splatting a scalar into a vector (insert then shuffle). The │
│ problem is dominance - not the operation semantics themselves.\n- Grep did    │
│ not find explicit references to InsertElement or ShuffleVector in             │
